reviewText: What a shame this series was cancelled although we still have Simon Baker in "The Mentalist". reviewText: This is just a warning about not being able to play either Season 1 or 2 on my blu-ray (Samsung) player.  The Guardian is great, and thank goodness I also have a multi-region DVD player or my husband and I would not have been able to watch these DVD's together.  I guess CBS has put encoding on the DVD's so they will not play on my blu-ray.  I did not send them back, because of being able to watch them on our multi-region DVD player, I don't know if anyone else has had this problem.  The blu-ray is 2 years old which is considered out of date.  I don't buy blu-rays because they usually will not play because of updated encoding so we can't duplicate them, which I would not do.  It plays all my other regular DVD's, but this is the first time we cannot get it to play a DVD.  Just be careful and I was curious if anyone else had this problem?
summary: Will not play on my Blu-Ray DVD Player

reviewText: This was a great second season for a legal / social services series. Simon Baker is as good as in Mentalist.I had not watched this on television and I was delighted to find this new series.It tells about an attorney Nick Fallin who has to do community service in a legal aid office to help social service and kids in need. He also helps other people in financial trouble while doing his daily business with mergers and acquisitions. This second season starts with Nick being in trouble because of his past drug probation sentencing. He had to be careful not be sentenced and going to jail. Luckily, his father is helping him and he avoids jailtime. He continues working in his firm with his father Fallin & Fallin and also at the legal services helping kids in need. He is still in love with Lulu his coworker.
summary: Even better than the first season

reviewText: Simon Baker is so given a much better script and character in the Guardian than he is in his current show The Mentalist.  Although he doesn't want to be a caring, involved person, he can't allow the injustice to children to continue,  This is a multifaceted show, that mixes social justice with business law.  It is intelligently done and shows us the cruelties of our world that still exist even though the show is over.  He is in this show a fairly silent person, who keeps most of his opinions and angers to himself.  Would that we all could do that and just take action.

reviewText: Have just a few more episodes of The Second Season to watch; and it's very different from the First Season.  How?Much more into the personal lives of the main characters (lots of sex). Still, this Second Season moves well and they tie the episodes together in an interesting way.  Not in exact chronological order; which i find an interesting change.  You see some follow-up 2 or 3 episodes later on some of the sub-plots.  The lead character (Nick) is not so stiff; even though he has to deal with some horrendous situations, shocking (very graphic), unexpected & well done.  There are a few 'sleepers' in the beginning that just did not measure up to the rest of the work.  But later on it gets back to it's high quality (interest holding) move along pace.Rita Moreno looks SO beautiful and well groomed with some of the finest cloths.  She adds a real interest as LuLu's Mother.
